      <div xml:id="NA268-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. (ET: tōḻi) itu talaimakaṟkuc (EN, ER, ET: talaimakaṭkuc) colliyatu.
            2. talaimakaṉ vantoḻukavum vēṟupāṭu kaṇṭāḷ “avaṉ varuvaṉ ākavu nī vēṟupaṭṭāy veṟi eṭuttuk koḷḷum vakaiyāṉ” eṉṟatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is what is said to HIM. 2. It is also how she who saw the changes when HE kept coming said “even though he come you have undergone changes, because of the wayin which the Veṟi [dance] has been set up.”</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA268">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            cūruṭai naṉantalaic cuṉainīr malka</l>
<l>            mālpeya ṟalaiiya maṉṉeṭuṅ kuṉṟattuk</l>
<l>            karuṅkāṟ kuṟiñci mataṉila vāṉpū</l>
<l>            vōvukkaṇ ṭaṉṉa vilvarai yiḻaitta</l>
<l>            nāṟukoḷ piraca mūṟu nāṭaṟkuk </l>
<l>            kātal ceytaluṅ kātala maṉmai</l>
<l>            yāteṉiṟ kollō tōḻi viṉavukam</l>
<l>            peymmaṇaṉ muṟṟaṅ kaṭikoṇṭu</l>
<l>            meymmali kaḻaṅkiṉ vēlaṟ ṟantē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>“Although making love</l>
<l>to the man from a land, where fragrant honeycombs are oozing,</l>
<l rend="indent">made within the limit of houses as if one saw a picture(?),<note place="foot">This whole line is rather enigmatic. Is this supposed to refer to bee husbandry? Or does <term xml:lang="ta">il</term> here refer to the single honey comb which contains the honey? And is the beehive itself a picturesque sight?</note> with</l>
<l rend="indent">the sky flowers of the fertile soil from the black-trunked Kuṟiñci</l>
<l rend="indent2">on the rich long hills on which great rain have poured</l>
<l rend="indent3">so that the water increases in the springs of fearful vast area<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cūruṭai</term> might refer to evil spirits roaming about, and <term xml:lang="ta">naṉantalai</term> might either mean a large mountain spring or the surroundings as such.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent4">[he has] no love for us.”<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kātalam aṉmai</term>: this is one of the typically under-marked main sentences, literally meaning no more than "absence of love". The <term xml:lang="ta">kātalam</term> can either be read as a 1.pl. (which would have to be interpreted as "absence of us being loved") or as an even more elliptical adjective formation.</note></l>
<l>– “What if you said [so], friend?”</l>
<l rend="indent4">we ask,</l>
<l>since the spear-bearing [priest] has been brought<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">taṇṭu</term> probably refers here to the usual sequence of events, that is, the mother having brought in the priest. T.V.G., however, suggests to read it as a causal instrumental here: because of the <term xml:lang="ta">Vēlaṉ</term>.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">with [his] truthful molucca beans,</l>
<l rend="indent4">the courtyard strewn with sand having taken scent.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
